Topic 6 Exercises: Selecting Model Terms

Madeline Olson

Theory

6.8.1

a

Best subset, because this model analyses every possible combination of predictors while the other methods build a model based on the previous iteration.

b

Best subset will most likely have the smallest test RSS for similar reasoning as in part a.

c

  1. T, the k+1-variable model is built from the k-variable model with the addition of another predictor
  2. T, the k-vairable model is made from the exclusion of a predictor from the k+1-variable model
  3. F, because these models are build from p or 1 predictors they may come to different conclusions about which predictors are significant
  4. F, same as c-iii.
  5. F, best subset analyses all combinations of predictors for different # of variables and between two models certain predictos may be swapped.

6.8.2

a

  1. similar to ridge regression, lasso method produces a less flexible model with decreased variance, just with fewer predictors

b

  1. ridge regression is less flexible and able to geratly decrease variance with little bias increase.

c

  1. non-linear methods are able to follow the data more closely than least squares but becasue of this they are likely to have high variance.

train=sample(1:dim(College)[1],(dim(College)[1]/2))
test=-train
College.train=College[train,]
College.test=College[test,]

lm.pred=predict(lm.fit, College.test)

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-10
x=model.matrix(Apps~., College[,-1])
y=College$Apps
grid=10^seq(10,-2,length=100)
ridge.mod=glmnet(x,y,alpha=0,lambda=grid)
Apps.test=College$Apps[test]
ridge.mod=glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha=0, lambda=grid, thresh=1e-12)
set.seed(1)
cv.out=cv.glmnet(x[train,],y[train], alpha=0)
plot(cv.out)

bestlam=cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
## [1] 440.9231
ridge.pred=predict(ridge.mod,s=bestlam,newx=x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred-Apps.test)^2)
